PART 5 : FEATURE ENGINEERING
Overview
All features are extracted from raw sensor and interaction events inside the SessionLevelFeatureExtractor class. The raw data is provided as a Python dictionary (session) containing:

navigation_events – list of screen transitions with timestamps and screen names.

touch_events – list of touch‑down/up pairs, coordinates, gesture types.

sensor_events – list of accelerometer and gyroscope readings with timestamps.

device_info – screen width and height for normalisation.

The extraction methods produce a flat dictionary of numerical features per session.
The full feature pool initially contained ~441 features; after expansions (per‑axis FFT, MFCC, multitaper, swipe geometry, etc.) the total exceeds 500 features.

Below, features are grouped by category, with formulas where applicable.

1. Navigation Features (6 features)
Method: extract_navigation_features

Input: navigation_events list.

Output: 6 numerical features.

Feature	Formula / Description
nav_total_screens	Number of screen transitions (len(nav))
nav_total_duration	Total session time from first to last navigation timestamp (ms).
nav_avg_time_per_screen	Mean of inter‑screen durations.
nav_flow_deviation	Count of screens that do not follow the expected flow (Start Screen → Register → …).
nav_back_navigation_count	Number of times the user navigated backwards in the expected flow.
nav_unique_screens	Number of distinct screens visited.
Why useful: Users have consistent navigation habits; impostors deviate.

2. Touch Features (~25 features, expanded with swipe geometry)
Method: extract_touch_features + _extract_swipe_geometry

Input: touch_events list, device_info for screen dimensions.

Output features (basic touch dynamics):

touch_count, touch_tap_ratio

Durations: touch_duration_mean, _std, _p5, _p95, _iqr

Inter‑touch intervals: touch_interval_mean, _std, _p5, _p95, _iqr

Velocities (normalised): touch_velocity_mean, _std, _p5, _p95, _iqr

Trigraph flight times: trigraph_flight_mean, _std, _p5, _p95, _iqr

Rhythm variance: trigraph_rhythm_variance_mean, _std

Normalisation: Coordinates are divided by screen width/height.
Velocity formula:
v_i = sqrt( (x_{i+1} - x_i)^2 + (y_{i+1} - y_i)^2 ) / Δt, where Δt is the time between touch‑up of event i and touch‑down of event i+1.

Swipe geometry (new):

swipe_angle_mean, _std – mean and std of arctan2(dy, dx)

swipe_path_mean, _std – direct distance between touch‑down and touch‑up (normalised)

swipe_straightness_mean – set to 1.0 in absence of raw touch‑move points

Why useful: Touch behaviour is highly individual – pressure, speed, rhythm, and swipe shape are biometric signatures.

3. Accelerometer Features (basic, ~30 features)
Method: extract_acc_features

Input: sensor_events → accelerometer readings per axis.

Calculates magnitude mag = sqrt(ax² + ay² + az²)

Extracts statistics for each axis (x, y, z) and for the magnitude.

Examples:

acc_magnitude_mean, _std, _skew, _kurtosis

acc_x_mean, _std, _skew, _kurtosis, _p5, _p50, _p95, _iqr

acc_jitter – mean absolute first difference of magnitude

acc_magnitude_jerk_mean, _std, _p5, _p95, _iqr (jerk is diff(mag))

Why useful: Captures device motion intensity, stability, and fine motor control.

4. Accelerometer Features – Magnitude Windowing (~80 features)
Method: extract_acc_features_mag_window

Process:

Low‑pass filter (Butterworth, 3rd order, cutoff=min(20, fs*0.4)).

Remove gravity using uniform filter (size = 5×fs).

Compute linear acceleration and magnitude.

Slide 5‑second windows with 50% overlap.

Within each window, compute for each axis (x, y, z, mag):

mean, std, skew, kurtosis, p5, p50, p95, iqr

energy = sum(signal²)/N

RMS = sqrt(mean(signal²))

jerk mean, std, p95

Also compute window‑level correlations (xy_corr, xz_corr, yz_corr) and SMA (Signal Magnitude Area) = sum(|wx|+|wy|+|wz|)/N.

Aggregate across windows by taking mean and std of each per‑window descriptor.

Final feature names: acc_x_mean_mean, acc_x_mean_std, …, acc_yz_corr_mean, acc_yz_corr_std.

Why useful: Captures temporal variability of motion patterns.

5. Gyroscope Features (~35 features, including wavelet)
Method: extract_gyro_features

Computes magnitude and per‑axis statistics similar to basic acc features.

Wavelet decomposition (db4, level 1): For each gyro axis, extracts:

wavelet_A_mean, _std, _energy, _max

wavelet_D1_mean, _std, _energy, _max

This adds ~24 features.

Why useful: Rotational motion is complementary to linear motion; wavelets capture transient events.

6. Touch‑Aligned Sensor Features (~30 features)
Method: extract_touch_sensor_features

For each touch, windows ±100 ms around touch‑down.

Collects accelerometer and gyroscope values in those windows.

Computes statistics (mean, std, variance, p05, p95, iqr) for each axis and for the magnitude, as well as axis correlations (touch_acc_corr_xy, etc.).

Why useful: Isolates sensor behaviour directly during touch interaction.

7. Fused Touch‑Sensor Features (pitch/roll, ~15 features)
Method: extract_fused_touch_sensor_features

Computes pitch and roll from accelerometer:
pitch = arctan(-ax / sqrt(ay² + az²))
roll = arctan(ay / az)

For each touch window (±100 ms), extracts mean/std of pitch, roll, gyro magnitude, and ratios (std/mean).

Then computes digraph (i→i+1) and trigraph (i→i+2) differences and aggregates mean/std.

Why useful: Hand grip orientation during touches is user‑specific.

8. HMOG (Hand Movement, Orientation, Grasp) Features (~120 features)
Method: extract_hmog_acc_gyro and extract_long_acc_gyro

For each touch event, windows before/during/after touch.

Extracts per‑axis and magnitude: mean during touch, std, net change, max change, time‑to‑peak, stability time, and STFT features (energy, entropy, peak frequency) from the surrounding ±200 ms window.

Example: touch_HMOG_acc_x_mean, touch_HMOG_gyro_mag_stft_energy.

Why useful: Core behavioural biometrics from the HMOG paper (Sitová et al. 2016). Captures micro‑movements during interaction.

9. Full‑Session FFT Features (Welch PSD, ~7 per signal → 56 total)
Method: _extract_windowed_fft

Process:

Slide 2‑second Hamming windows with 50% overlap on the active signal.
Compute Welch PSD (nperseg=32, spectrum scaling).
For each window, extract:
Peak frequency: frequency bin with maximum power.
Spectral energy: sum of power.
Spectral entropy: -sum(prob * log(prob)) / log(len(prob)) where prob = power / sum(power).
Spectral centroid: sum(f * power) / sum(power).
Spectral medoid: frequency where cumulative energy reaches 50%.
Band energy low (0.5–2 Hz) and mid (2–5 Hz).
Aggregate across windows by taking the mean of each descriptor.
Applied to: acc_mag, gyro_mag and each axis (acc_x, acc_y, acc_z, gyro_x, gyro_y, gyro_z) → 8 signals.

Feature names: acc_fft_peak_freq, acc_x_fft_spectral_energy, gyro_z_fft_band_mid_2_5hz, etc.

Why useful: Frequency‑domain motion patterns (rhythm, vibration) are discriminative.

10. MFCC Features (Mel‑Frequency Cepstral Coefficients, ~18 per signal → 144 total)
Method: _extract_mfcc_features

Process:

Slide windows (2 s, Hamming).
FFT → magnitude spectrum.
Apply 12 triangular mel‑scaled filters (adapted for 0.5 to fs/2 Hz).
Log energies → Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT) to obtain 6 cepstral coefficients.
Across windows, compute mean, std, and delta (first‑order temporal difference) of each coefficient.
Feature names: acc_x_mfcc_0_mean, acc_x_mfcc_0_std, acc_x_mfcc_0_delta, …

Why useful: Cepstral coefficients compactly capture the spectral envelope; widely used in speaker recognition, adapted here for motion signals. Decorrelated, robust, and highly individual.

11. Multitaper Spectral Features (~7 per signal → 56 total)
Method: _extract_multitaper_features

Process:

Slide windows (2 s).
Apply 3 DPSS tapers → average periodograms (reduces variance).
Extract the same 7 descriptors as windowed FFT (peak freq, energy, entropy, centroid, medoid, low/mid band energies).
Aggregate by mean across windows.
Feature names: acc_mag_mt_peak_freq, gyro_x_mt_spectral_entropy, …

Why useful: More stable spectral estimates → lower intra‑user variance.

12. Correlation Features
Inter‑sensor (acc vs gyro, 6 features)
Method: extract_inter_sensor_correlations

acc_gyro_mag_corr, acc_gyro_motion_corr, acc_x_gyro_x_corr, acc_y_gyro_y_corr, acc_z_gyro_z_corr, acc_gyro_mean_axis_corr.

Motion correlation uses high‑pass filtered (3rd order, cutoff 0.1 Hz) accelerometer to remove gravity.

Intra‑sensor (within sensor, 6 features)
Method: extract_intra_sensor_correlations

acc_x_y_corr, acc_x_z_corr, acc_y_z_corr (same for gyro).

Lag correlation (5 features)
Method: extract_lag_correlation_features

Cross‑correlation between acc and gyro magnitudes.

Finds lag (in samples and ms) where correlation is maximum.

acc_gyro_max_lag_corr, acc_gyro_zero_lag_corr, acc_gyro_lag_corr_diff.

Touch‑motion correlations (8 features)
Method: extract_touch_motion_correlations

motion_touch_idle_corr, touch_accel_energy_ratio, gyro_touch_idle_corr, etc.

Measures synchronisation between touch activity and motion.

Why useful: Sensor coupling and lead‑lag relationships are hard to mimic.

13. HMOG Grasp Stability (Simplified, ~24 features)
Method: extract_hmog_grasp_stability_simplified

For each touch, analyses the pre‑/during‑/post‑touch sensor windows.

For each signal axis and magnitude, computes:

peak_amplitude (max − pre‑touch mean)

recovery_percentage (post − during) / peak_amplitude

post_tap_variability (std after / std before)

Aggregates by mean across touches.

Feature names: hmog_stab_acc_mag_peak_amplitude, …

Why useful: Quantifies how much a tap perturbs the device and how quickly the user stabilises.

14. Jerk Smoothness Features (~9 features)
Method: extract_jerk_smoothness_features

Computes acceleration magnitude jerk (absolute first difference).

Extracts: jerk_mean, _std, _p25, _p50, _p75, _iqr, smoothness_index (1 / mean jerk), jerk_peak_rate, jerk_high_freq_energy (FFT of jerk in 3‑8 Hz band).

Why useful: Smoothness of motion is a biometric trait.

15. DTW (Dynamic Time Warping) Features (~16 features)
Method: extract_dtw_features

Requires pre‑computed centroids and medoids (templates) for various sensor axes and magnitude.

Computes DTW distance between the session’s time series and the templates.

Feature names: acc_x_dtw_centroid, gyro_mag_dtw_medoid, …

Why useful: Captures similarity of the entire motion sequence to the user’s template.

Scaling and Imputation
No scaling during feature extraction – raw numerical values are stored.

Before model training, StandardScaler is fitted on the genuine training data of the user (or the LOUO training set) and applied to all features.

Missing values during extraction are handled by returning zero in early‑exit defaults. In Phase 1, missing values are imputed with median. In the tuning scripts, fillna(median) is used.
